      "writtenOn": "2021-05-13T12:53:58Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Theoretically, without memory barriers, there\u0027s a possibility for this write to become visible in the render thread after it processes kDestroy -- which would cause it to miss the event and block in ALooper_pollAll indefinitely.  In practice I doubt that can happen, but to harden we could:\n\n  a) use std::atomic\u003cbool\u003e + appropriate std::memory_order for store/load (prolly release/acquire, respectively)\n  b) pass a non-zero timeout to ALooper_pollAll to wake up periodically and re-check the flag\n  c) update the flag from the render thread (e.g. in the kDestroy handler) instead of SurfaceThread::release()\n\nI\u0027m not super worried about it, but option c) seems like a clean, straightforward change.",
      "revId": "dc9e76b5357d14e3adbd84297e351da37b7904b1",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02"
    },
